17 14–301.1.
18 THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY FINDS THE FOLLOWING:
19 (1) THE STATE OF MARYLAND SEEKS TO ENSURE THAT ALL CITIZENS
20 OF THE STATE HAVE EQUAL ACCESS TO BUSINESS FORMATION AND BUSINESS
21 GROWTH OPPORTUNITIES;
22 (2) THE ELIMINATION OF DISCRIMINATION AGAINST MINORITY– AND
23 WOMEN–OWNED BUSINESSES IS OF PARAMOUNT IMPORTANCE TO THE FUTURE
24 WELFARE OF ALL MARYLANDERS AND THE STATE;
25 (3) THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY HAS ACCEPTED AND CAREFULLY
26 REVIEWED THE DISPARITY STUDY ENTITLED “STATE OF MARYLAND 2025 MINORITY
27 BUSINESS ENTERPRISE DISPARITY STUDY” (THE STUDY) AND FINDS THAT THE
28 STUDY PROVIDES A STRONG BASIS IN EVIDENCE DEMONSTRATING PERSISTENT
29 INTENTIONAL DISCRIMINATION AGAINST MINORITY– AND WOMEN–OWNED
30 BUSINESSES;
31 (4) BASED ON THE REVIEW BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE
32 STUDY, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY FINDS THAT:
33 (I) BASED ON RIGOROUS ECONOMETRICS ANALYSES THAT
34 CONTROL FOR KEY FACTORS, THERE ARE SUBSTANTIAL AND STATISTICALLY
35 SIGNIFICANT ADVERSE DISPARITIES THAT ARE CONSISTENT WITH DISCRIMINATION

6 HOUSE BILL 1578
1 AGAINST MINORITIES AND NONMINORITY WOMEN IN WAGES, FIRM FORMATION,
2 ENTREPRENEURIAL EARNINGS, AND ACCESS TO CAPITAL IN THE PRIVATE SECTOR
3 IN THE SAME GEOGRAPHIC MARKETS AND INDUSTRY CATEGORIES IN WHICH THE
4 STATE DOES BUSINESS;
5 (II) A THOROUGH EXAMINATION OF THE LITERATURE REVEALS
6 SEVERE AND PERSISTENT INTENTIONAL DISPARITIES AND DISCRIMINATION IN
7 ACCESS TO PRIVATE BUSINESS CAPITAL MARKETS THAT IN SOME CASES HAVE BEEN
8 CAUSED BY GOVERNMENT POLICIES;
9 (III) THE STATE WOULD BECOME A PASSIVE PARTICIPANT IN
10 PRIVATE SECTOR RACIAL AND GENDER DISCRIMINATION IF IT CEASED OR
11 CURTAILED REMEDIAL EFFORTS OF THE STATE, INCLUDING THE OPERATION OF
12 THE MINORITY BUSINESS ENTERPRISE PROGRAM;
13 (IV) THERE ARE SUBSTANTIAL, ADVERSE, AND STATISTICALLY
14 SIGNIFICANT DISPARITIES THAT ARE CONSISTENT WITH DISCRIMINATION AGAINST
15 MINORITIES AND NONMINORITY WOMEN IN STATE PROCUREMENT;
16 (V) THESE SUBSTANTIAL, ADVERSE, AND STATISTICALLY
17 SIGNIFICANT DISPARITIES ARE CONSISTENT WITH DISCRIMINATION AGAINST ALL
18 INDIVIDUAL MINORITY GROUPS AND FOR NONMINORITY WOMEN IN MOST MAJOR
19 INDUSTRY CATEGORIES IN STATE PROCUREMENT;
20 (VI) THERE IS SIGNIFICANT EVIDENCE THAT DISCRIMINATION IN
21 THE PRIVATE SECTOR HAS DEPRESSED FIRM FORMATION AND FIRM GROWTH
22 AMONG MINORITY AND NONMINORITY WOMEN ENTREPRENEURS, DECREASING THE
23 AVAILABILITY OF MINORITIES AND NONMINORITY WOMEN FOR PUBLIC AND
24 PRIVATE CONTRACTING; AND
25 (VII) THERE IS POWERFUL AND PERSUASIVE EVIDENCE, BOTH
26 STATISTICAL AND QUALITATIVE, OF INTENTIONAL DISCRIMINATION, INCLUDING
27 DISCRIMINATION BY GOVERNMENT ACTORS, AGAINST MINORITY AND NONMINORITY
28 WOMEN BUSINESS OWNERS IN BOTH THE PUBLIC AND PRIVATE SECTORS;
29 (5) AS A RESULT OF ONGOING DISCRIMINATION AND THE
30 PRESENT–DAY EFFECTS OF PAST DISCRIMINATION, MINORITY– AND WOMEN–OWNED
31 BUSINESSES COMBINED CONTINUE TO BE SIGNIFICANTLY UNDERUTILIZED
32 RELATIVE TO THE AVAILABILITY OF MINORITIES AND NONMINORITY WOMEN TO
33 PERFORM WORK IN THE OVERWHELMING MAJORITY OF THE PROCUREMENT
34 CATEGORIES IN WHICH THE STATE DOES BUSINESS;

HOUSE BILL 1578 7
1 (6) MINORITY PRIME CONTRACTORS ALSO ARE SUBJECT TO
2 DISCRIMINATION AND CONFRONT ESPECIALLY DAUNTING BARRIERS IN
3 ATTEMPTING TO COMPETE WITH VERY LARGE AND LONG–ESTABLISHED
4 NONMINORITY COMPANIES;
5 (7) DESPITE THE FACT THAT THE STATE HAS EMPLOYED, AND
6 CONTINUES TO EMPLOY, NUMEROUS AND ROBUST RACE–NEUTRAL REMEDIES,
7 INCLUDING AGGRESSIVE OUTREACH AND ADVERTISING, TRAINING AND EDUCATION,
8 SMALL BUSINESS PROGRAMS, EFFORTS TO IMPROVE ACCESS TO CAPITAL, AND
9 OTHER EFFORTS, THERE IS A STRONG BASIS IN EVIDENCE THAT DISCRIMINATION
10 PERSISTS EVEN IN PUBLIC SECTOR PROCUREMENT IN WHICH THESE EFFORTS HAVE
11 BEEN EMPLOYED;
12 (8) NOTWITHSTANDING THE LEVELS OF PARTICIPATION ACHIEVED
13 WHEN RACE–CONSCIOUS MEASURES ARE USED, THERE IS CONCERN THAT, IN THE
14 ABSENCE OF MINORITY BUSINESS ENTERPRISE PARTICIPATION GOALS FOR STATE
15 PROCUREMENT, THERE WOULD BE A SUBSTANTIAL DECREASE IN THE OVERALL
16 UTILIZATION OF MINORITY– AND WOMEN–OWNED BUSINESSES;
17 (9) THIS SUBTITLE ENSURES THAT RACE–NEUTRAL EFFORTS WILL BE
18 USED TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT FEASIBLE AND THAT RACE–CONSCIOUS MEASURES
19 WILL BE USED ONLY WHERE NECESSARY TO ELIMINATE DISCRIMINATION THAT WAS
20 NOT ALLEVIATED BY RACE–NEUTRAL EFFORTS;
21 (10) THIS SUBTITLE CONTINUES AND ENHANCES EFFORTS TO ENSURE
22 THAT THE STATE LIMITS THE BURDEN ON NONMINORITY, MALE–OWNED
23 BUSINESSES AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE BY ENSURING THAT ALL GOALS ARE DEVELOPED
24 USING THE BEST AVAILABLE DATA, WAIVERS ARE AVAILABLE WHENEVER
25 CONTRACTORS MAKE GOOD FAITH EFFORTS, AND THAT NONMINORITY MEN MAY
26 QUALIFY FOR CERTIFICATION IF NONMINORITY MEN ARE SOCIALLY AND
27 ECONOMICALLY DISADVANTAGED;
28 (11) THIS SUBTITLE ENSURES THAT THE OPERATION OF THE
29 MINORITY BUSINESS ENTERPRISE PROGRAM IS CONSISTENT WITH THE STUDY
30 DATA AND NARROWLY TAILORED TO THE COMPELLING INTERESTS OF THE STATE;
31 AND
32 (12) STATE EFFORTS TO SUPPORT THE DEVELOPMENT OF
33 COMPETITIVELY VIABLE MINORITY– AND WOMEN–OWNED BUSINESS ENTERPRISES
34 WILL HELP REDUCE DISCRIMINATION, CREATE JOBS FOR ALL CITIZENS OF
35 MARYLAND, HELP GROW THE MARYLAND ECONOMY, AND FOSTER COMPETITION
36 THAT WILL REDUCE THE COST OF GOODS AND SERVICES PROCURED BY THE STATE.

